In a Gene Wolfe story it is mentioned how a hospital patient is able to request to get taken/wheeled by a nurse to the hospital rooftop for a few hours in the sunlight if he wishes, but many patients didn't know it was an option. Probably still a legal tradition at some places.

Back in the day medicine recognized how important sunlight is. I remember reading about Great War era hospitals wheeling patients outside every day, I think they even put beds outside for patients to spend the day in sunlight at some places, mountain tuberculosis sanatoriums too.

A fellow medbro commented he noticed old hospitals always have tall, wide windows, while new ones do not. It all loops back to architecture, probably open windows blasting raw sunlight in the room works better to prevent hospital infections than all the over the top hygiene stuff
